To start building a website like the one shown, you can begin with a basic HTML skeleton and progressively embellish it with CSS for styling. Here's a step-by-step guide to get you started:

1. **Basic HTML Structure**:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Website Title</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div id="header">
        <a href="#" id="logo"><img src="logo.png" alt="Logo"></a>
        <ul id="menu">
            <li><a href="#">Home</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Services</a></li>
            <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="content">
        <h1>Giveaway of Sothink Flash Menu is over!</h1>
        <div class="product">
            <img src="flash_menu.jpg" alt="Sothink Flash Menu">
            <p>An ultimate Flash menu builder creates stylish & stunning cross-browser Flash drop down menu in clicks. 68 built-in templates, 50 amazing special effects, 35 preset styles and image library of 4 categories, make SE friendly navigation bar without Flash and ActionScript skills.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="product">
            <img src="swf_decompiler.jpg" alt="Sothink SWF Decompiler">
            <p>A high-performance Flash decompiler for you to convert SWF to FLA or FLEX precisely; Easily extract all Flash resources; Convert Flash to html5 files; Replace image/shape/text/sound for SWF. It is the first decompiler to get XFL from Flash CS5 SWF.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="product">
            <img src="swf_quicker.jpg" alt="Sothink SWF Quicker">
            <p>Provide a much Quicker way to build your own flash animation, powerful but easy-to-use. (With almost all the function that Adobe Flash has, but much cheaper than it)Stronger functions but lower price!</p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div id="footer">
        <p>Sothink is a trademark of SourceTec Software Co., LTD.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

2. **CSS for Styling**: Create a separate CSS file (e.g., `styles.css`) to handle the styling. A basic example to get you started:
```css
body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    color: #333;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}
.header {
    background-color: #024770;
    padding: 20px;
}
#menu {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
}
#menu li {
    display: inline;
    margin-right: 20px;
}
.product {
    margin: 20px;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
}
#footer {
    background-color: #000;
    color: #fff;
    text-align: center;
    padding: 10px;
}
```
3. **Images and Resources**: Make sure to have the images like `logo.png`, `flash_menu.jpg`, etc., in a folder accessible to your HTML file.

This structure sets up a foundational layout for your website. You can expand upon this by adding more styles, interactive elements, and advanced features as needed.
